150
00:14:45,468 --> 00:14:47,803
I fall crazy in love with a Polish shiksa.

151
00:14:48,388 --> 00:14:49,888
What is that? What is a "shiksa"?

152
00:14:49,973 --> 00:14:54,309
A shiksa is a goy girl.
A lady of the Gentile persuasion.

153
00:14:56,104 --> 00:14:57,279
She's a...

154
00:14:57,814 --> 00:15:01,316
All right. I just assumed that she was...

155
00:15:02,110 --> 00:15:03,902
- She was Jewish?
- Yeah.

156
00:15:03,987 --> 00:15:05,153
Jewish?

157
00:15:05,321 --> 00:15:08,824
No, no, no.
No, our Sophie is Catholic.

158
00:15:10,702 --> 00:15:14,288
Yeah. Well, it's okay,
but I'm not anymore Catholic, so.

159
00:15:14,831 --> 00:15:16,373
Well, Catholic-ish.

160
00:15:17,834 --> 00:15:20,168
When I first met this one here,

161
00:15:20,503 --> 00:15:23,255
she was a rag and a bone
and a hank of hair.

162
00:15:23,715 --> 00:15:25,340
And that was a whole year-and-a-half

163
00:15:25,425 --> 00:15:28,260
after the Russians had liberated
the camp she was in.

164
00:15:28,344 --> 00:15:32,514
Yeah, it looked like something
that scares the birds.

165
00:15:32,724 --> 00:15:35,851
What is that? Scarecrow.

166
00:15:37,253 --> 00:15:38,645
I had "scurbut."

167
00:15:38,730 --> 00:15:41,398
No, no, no! She means scurvy.

168
00:15:41,691 --> 00:15:44,401
And typhus and anemia and scarlet fever.

169
00:15:44,485 --> 00:15:47,112
It was a fucking miracle
that she emerged from that camp alive.

170
00:15:47,196 --> 00:15:48,280
Right.

171
00:15:48,364 --> 00:15:52,034
I mean, I thought that I had leukemia.

172
00:15:54,579 --> 00:15:56,455
I thought I was dying.

173
00:15:57,206 --> 00:16:00,834
But it was Nathan that see
that it was only anemia.

174
00:16:01,544 --> 00:16:02,502
Are you a doctor?

175
00:16:02,587 --> 00:16:03,587
No, no.

176
00:16:03,671 --> 00:16:05,631
That's my brother's domain.

177
00:16:05,715 --> 00:16:06,673
But I'm a biologist.

178
00:16:06,758 --> 00:16:07,758
Yeah!

179
00:16:08,301 --> 00:16:10,385
- I graduated in science from Harvard.
- Harvard.

180
00:16:10,470 --> 00:16:11,521
And he...

181
00:16:12,805 --> 00:16:17,267
MA in Developmental and Cellular Biology.

182
00:16:18,561 --> 00:16:19,645
I do research now.

183
00:16:19,729 --> 00:16:20,687
He works at Pfizer.

184
00:16:20,772 --> 00:16:23,815
Pfizer, it's a big pharmaceutical house
here in Brooklyn.

185
00:16:23,900 --> 00:16:27,069
Anyway, I took her to this friend
of my brother's,

186
00:16:27,153 --> 00:16:29,488
a doctor who teaches up
at Columbia Presbyterian.

187
00:16:29,614 --> 00:16:30,697
Yeah.

188
00:16:30,782 --> 00:16:32,866
He confirmed my diagnosis.

189
00:16:33,076 --> 00:16:35,327
And we put the little sweetie here

190
00:16:35,411 --> 00:16:37,913
on massive doses of ferrous sulfate

191
00:16:38,915 --> 00:16:41,416
and she began to bloom like a rose.

192
00:16:42,794 --> 00:16:44,010
A rose.

193
00:16:44,962 --> 00:16:46,213
A rose.

194
00:16:48,007 --> 00:16:50,050
A beautiful fucking rose.

195
00:16:53,429 --> 00:16:55,097
You're something.

196
00:16:55,598 --> 00:16:58,725
Thank you for making me
to bloom like a rose.

197
00:17:08,611 --> 00:17:11,029
Not "to bloom," just "bloom."

198
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:12,698
She's so good.
It's about time she was perfect.

199
00:17:12,782 --> 00:17:16,118
"To bloom." So what?
I mean, this is a ridiculous language!

200
00:17:16,202 --> 00:17:17,911
There's too many words!

201
00:17:17,995 --> 00:17:22,207
The word for "velocity," okay,
there's "fast, quick, rapid,"

202
00:17:22,291 --> 00:17:24,126
and they all mean the same thing.

203
00:17:24,210 --> 00:17:25,377
Swift, speedy.

204
00:17:25,461 --> 00:17:26,586
Hasty.

205
00:17:26,963 --> 00:17:28,422
- Fleet.
- Brisk.

206
00:17:28,756 --> 00:17:30,716
- Expeditious.
- Accelerated.

207
00:17:30,800 --> 00:17:32,092
Winged.

208
00:17:32,552 --> 00:17:34,803
No, no! Stop it!

209
00:17:35,722 --> 00:17:37,305
It's ridiculous!

210
00:17:37,890 --> 00:17:41,560
In French, it's so easy.
You say <i>vite.</i>

211
00:17:41,644 --> 00:17:44,855
Or in Polish, <i>szybko,</i>
and in Russian, <i>bystro.</i>

212
00:17:44,939 --> 00:17:48,525
It's only in the English it's so complicated!

213
00:17:48,609 --> 00:17:50,026
How many languages do you know?

214
00:17:50,111 --> 00:17:52,738
Well, my father was a linguist,
so I mean, I...

215
00:17:52,822 --> 00:17:56,491
He teach me German, French, Russian, Hungarian,

216
00:17:56,576 --> 00:17:58,410
the Slavic languages.

217
00:17:59,162 --> 00:18:02,664
So, what language I am butchering now?

218
00:18:03,583 --> 00:18:04,750
English!

219
00:18:04,959 --> 00:18:07,961
I bet your father was
a very interesting man.

220
00:18:12,300 --> 00:18:14,301
Yeah, my father was

221
00:18:16,345 --> 00:18:17,971
a civilized man.

222
00:18:22,435 --> 00:18:25,187
That's the word, yeah? "Civilized"?

223
00:18:25,563 --> 00:18:27,439
- Very good word.
- Yeah?

224
00:18:27,523 --> 00:18:31,276
My father was a civilized man
living in a non-civilized time.

225
00:18:31,861 --> 00:18:34,780
The civilized, they was the first to die.

226
00:18:37,200 --> 00:18:39,117
Do you play the piano?

227
00:18:39,410 --> 00:18:42,037
No. I used to play, but I...

228
00:18:45,750 --> 00:18:47,501
I no longer play.

229
00:18:49,879 --> 00:18:51,546
I don't anymore.

230
00:18:52,715 --> 00:18:55,175
My mother was a beautiful pianist.

231
00:19:00,890 --> 00:19:05,060
Nathan surprised me
with that piano on my birthday!

232
00:19:31,462 --> 00:19:33,171
I love that piece.

233
00:19:48,729 --> 00:19:50,272
When I was a little girl,

234
00:19:51,566 --> 00:19:53,650
I remember, I'd lay in bed

235
00:19:53,734 --> 00:19:57,404
and I'd hear my mother downstairs
playing the piano,

236
00:19:59,615 --> 00:20:02,367
and the sound of my father's typewriter.

237
00:20:05,204 --> 00:20:10,500
I think no child has a more
wonderful father and mother.

238
00:20:16,632 --> 00:20:18,550
And a more beautiful life.

239
00:20:36,152 --> 00:20:37,819
<i>Swanee,</i> you know that song, right?

240
00:20:53,878 --> 00:20:55,170
Stingo, hit it!

241
00:21:59,902 --> 00:22:02,404
Oh, God!

242
00:22:02,571 --> 00:22:05,073
<i>Suddenly, I shivered violently.</i>

243
00:22:06,492 --> 00:22:09,619
<i>I remembered Nathan's voice
that night before.</i>

244
00:22:11,247 --> 00:22:14,833
<i>"Don't you see, Sophie?
We are dying."</i>

245
00:22:16,043 --> 00:22:18,545
<i>I longed desperately to escape,</i>

246
00:22:19,255 --> 00:22:21,423
<i>to pack my bags and flee.</i>

247
00:22:22,216 --> 00:22:23,758
<i>But I did not.</i>

248
00:22:25,469 --> 00:22:27,679
<i>I stayed at Yetta Zimmerman's,</i>

249
00:22:27,763 --> 00:22:32,392
<i>and thus I helped fulfill Sophie's prophecy
about the three of us.</i>

250
00:22:32,476 --> 00:22:34,978
<i>We became the best of friends.</i>

251
00:24:11,200 --> 00:24:16,246
Here is an example of how emotionally
evocative English can be.

252
00:24:16,330 --> 00:24:19,624
<i>Sophie loved to tell
how Nathan saved her life.</i>

253
00:24:20,501 --> 00:24:24,129
<i>Their meeting was, for her, a miracle.</i>

254
00:24:24,213 --> 00:24:26,965
"Because I could not stop for Death,

255
00:24:27,216 --> 00:24:30,135
