00:46:07,598 --> 00:46:08,807
His writings.

515
00:46:08,891 --> 00:46:12,644
Well, one day, I was at the Mass

516
00:46:14,105 --> 00:46:15,605
and I have a...

517
00:46:18,276 --> 00:46:21,736
I had a presentiment.

518
00:46:23,030 --> 00:46:25,782
I had many fears and I...

519
00:46:25,867 --> 00:46:29,453
I run out of the church
and I go to the university,

520
00:46:29,537 --> 00:46:32,497
and I see that the gate is locked.

521
00:46:33,791 --> 00:46:36,418
And there were many, many Germans there.

522
00:46:38,379 --> 00:46:41,548
And I saw the professors.
They was loading them into the truck.

523
00:46:41,632 --> 00:46:45,719
And this one part of canvas has moved away.

524
00:46:46,554 --> 00:46:50,974
And I see my father's face
and the face of my husband behind him.

525
00:46:52,518 --> 00:46:53,977
And...

526
00:46:56,481 --> 00:46:57,981
I looked.

527
00:46:59,984 --> 00:47:01,902
But the German, he pulled that away

528
00:47:01,986 --> 00:47:05,280
and I never saw those faces again.

529
00:47:05,364 --> 00:47:07,157
They took them to Sachsenhausen, you know.

530
00:47:07,241 --> 00:47:10,494
That's a German work camp,
but they shot them the next day.

531
00:47:10,578 --> 00:47:12,787
That's what we have heard.

532
00:47:17,293 --> 00:47:18,460
Your mother?

533
00:47:18,544 --> 00:47:19,669
My mother...

534
00:47:20,880 --> 00:47:22,380
My mother got

535
00:47:24,759 --> 00:47:27,928
tuberculosis and...

536
00:47:29,847 --> 00:47:32,307
Oh, she is very sick, you know.

537
00:47:32,391 --> 00:47:35,894
She started to die of that,
and I can't do anything.

538
00:47:38,523 --> 00:47:41,441
But I think if I could get <i>mieso...</i>

539
00:47:41,526 --> 00:47:44,986
If I could get that meat for my mother,
I would make her strong.

540
00:47:45,071 --> 00:47:47,280
So I go to the country,

541
00:47:48,115 --> 00:47:51,868
and the peasants there,
they're selling ham.

542
00:47:52,870 --> 00:47:56,289
And I go with that black market money,

543
00:47:56,374 --> 00:47:58,750
I buy that and I bring it back.

544
00:47:58,834 --> 00:48:00,418
But, you know,
this is forbidden because

545
00:48:00,503 --> 00:48:03,421
all the meat goes to the Germans, you know.

546
00:48:03,506 --> 00:48:05,131
If you get caught...

547
00:48:05,216 --> 00:48:09,553
So I hid the ham under my skirt
on the train.

548
00:48:09,637 --> 00:48:12,556
I'm pretending that I'm pregnant, you know.

549
00:48:13,082 --> 00:48:14,599
I was so afraid!

550
00:48:15,309 --> 00:48:16,643
I was shaking.

551
00:48:16,727 --> 00:48:19,020
And then that German,

552
00:48:21,399 --> 00:48:24,901
who was in the front of the train,
and he saw me.

553
00:48:24,986 --> 00:48:27,904
And I'm sitting there
and he came up to me

554
00:48:27,989 --> 00:48:30,824
and he take under my skirt that ham.

555
00:48:37,957 --> 00:48:40,417
So they sent me to Auschwitz.

556
00:48:42,962 --> 00:48:46,256
You were sent to Auschwitz
because you stole a ham?

557
00:48:46,340 --> 00:48:50,135
No. I was sent to Auschwitz
because they saw that I was afraid.

558
00:48:53,639 --> 00:48:55,265
Oh, yeah.

559
00:48:56,475 --> 00:48:57,601
You know what that means?

560
00:48:57,685 --> 00:48:58,727
Yeah.

561
00:48:59,770 --> 00:49:02,439
You tried to commit suicide in Auschwitz?

562
00:49:03,649 --> 00:49:06,234
No, it was after that.

563
00:49:06,319 --> 00:49:08,278
After that, I was in...

564
00:49:11,490 --> 00:49:12,866
After liberation.

565
00:49:12,950 --> 00:49:14,326
After you were safe?

566
00:49:14,952 --> 00:49:16,786
Yes, safe, yeah.

567
00:49:18,205 --> 00:49:22,626
I was safe. I was in Sweden.
I was in that refugee camp.

568
00:49:24,045 --> 00:49:27,339
I mean, that was good.
They try to help you, you know.

569
00:49:27,423 --> 00:49:29,799
They try to...

570
00:49:29,884 --> 00:49:32,385
They try, but...

571
00:49:38,017 --> 00:49:39,517
I knew that

572
00:49:41,228 --> 00:49:46,775
Christ had turned his face away from me.

573
00:49:47,860 --> 00:49:51,655
And that only a Jesus
who no longer cared for me

574
00:49:51,739 --> 00:49:54,908
could kill those people that I love,

575
00:49:57,161 --> 00:50:01,915
but leave me alive with my shame.

576
00:50:01,999 --> 00:50:04,959
Oh, God. So I went to that church.

577
00:50:05,711 --> 00:50:08,088
And I took the glass, I knelt down

578
00:50:08,172 --> 00:50:12,384
and I cut my wrist.

579
00:50:12,468 --> 00:50:15,428
But I didn't die, of course.

580
00:50:17,181 --> 00:50:19,099
Of course not.

581
00:50:30,861 --> 00:50:35,323
Stingo, there's so many things
you don't understand.

582
00:50:38,077 --> 00:50:41,538
There's so many things that I

583
00:50:42,289 --> 00:50:45,792
cannot tell you.

584
00:50:45,918 --> 00:50:47,636
I want you to trust me.

585
00:50:51,507 --> 00:50:53,842
I want you to trust me.

586
00:50:55,761 --> 00:50:57,387
Just trust me.

587
00:51:08,983 --> 00:51:12,652
Oh, God! There is Nathan!

588
00:51:14,947 --> 00:51:16,406
Nathan!

589
00:51:18,117 --> 00:51:20,493
- Sophie!
- Astrid!

590
00:51:22,329 --> 00:51:25,373
I'm working night duty
at Brooklyn Hospital this week.

591
00:51:25,458 --> 00:51:27,751
My patient is this old lady
who's meaner than my mother,

592
00:51:27,835 --> 00:51:29,002
if you can believe.

593
00:51:29,086 --> 00:51:32,380
Well, good night, Astrid.
Have a good sleep.

594
00:51:33,966 --> 00:51:36,676
That was Astrid, you know.

595
00:51:36,761 --> 00:51:38,344
Maybe I'll leave the door open.

596
00:51:38,429 --> 00:51:40,722
In case he comes, we could hear him.

597
00:51:40,806 --> 00:51:42,348
So you want another drink?

598
00:51:44,101 --> 00:51:45,894
- Your bottle is empty.
- Well...

599
00:51:47,188 --> 00:51:50,523
Oh, I know where Nathan keeps
another bottle.

600
00:51:54,153 --> 00:51:56,488
Be careful, it's dark in here.

601
00:52:02,495 --> 00:52:03,745
Oh, God.

602
00:52:03,829 --> 00:52:07,499
I think you'll feel better
if we just call him at the lab.

603
00:52:08,542 --> 00:52:10,210
I can't do that.

604
00:52:10,294 --> 00:52:14,964
I mean, he doesn't like for me to call him.
You know, at work.

605
00:52:15,299 --> 00:52:17,592
So, anyway.

606
00:52:18,969 --> 00:52:21,054
I did it an hour ago.

607
00:52:21,180 --> 00:52:23,932
And there was no answer, so.

608
00:52:24,016 --> 00:52:25,517
I'm sure the switchboard's just shut off.

609
00:52:25,601 --> 00:52:28,978
Yes, I think that's right.
I'm sure that...

610
00:52:29,063 --> 00:52:31,397
You know, sometimes when
he can't sleep at night,

611
00:52:31,482 --> 00:52:34,901
he goes and he walks
all over the city.

612
00:52:35,027 --> 00:52:38,488
Yeah, he goes into all these neighborhoods.

613
00:52:38,572 --> 00:52:42,534
I mean, I don't know where he goes,
but once he came back,

614
00:52:42,618 --> 00:52:48,414
he had a black eye and his jaw
was all swollen there.

615
00:52:48,499 --> 00:52:51,251
Yeah, I thought it was broken.

616
00:52:54,588 --> 00:52:57,257
You know, he could be hurt.

617
00:52:57,341 --> 00:53:01,553
I don't know where he is, but I think
we should call the police right now.

618
00:53:01,637 --> 00:53:04,472
No, look, I think we ought to wait two hours.

619
00:53:04,598 --> 00:53:07,225
You know, just wait till somebody
is on the switchboard there.

620
00:53:07,309 --> 00:53:08,685
We'll just call him then.

621
00:53:08,769 --> 00:53:12,689
He's working late. He probably
just got tired and fell asleep there.

622
00:53:12,773 --> 00:53:16,442
Yeah. He's probably asleep there.

623
00:53:18,529 --> 00:53:19,529
I'm sure.

624
00:53:19,613 --> 00:53:21,114
I'm sure you're right.

625
00:53:26,120 --> 00:53:28,454
Look at this. <i>The Nazi Primer.</i>

626
00:53:31,542 --> 00:53:34,252
He must have everything ever written
about the Nazis in those years.

627
00:53:34,336 --> 00:53:38,332
Yes, he is obsessed with the Nazis
that are escaping justice.

628
00:53:40,259 --> 00:53:42,802
Do you suppose all this started
after he met you?

629
00:53:43,053 --> 00:53:46,890
Look, I know I shouldn't tell him
about that place,

630
00:53:46,974 --> 00:53:48,766
but what could I do?

631
00:53:48,851 --> 00:53:51,769
- I know it's my fault that he...
- Look, I can understand.

632
00:53:52,646 --> 00:53:53,980
After all, he is a Jew.

633
00:53:54,940 --> 00:53:58,693
Yes, he is a Jew,
but don't you think that I'm angry, too?

634
00:53:58,777 --> 00:54:03,072
That these men, these terrible Nazis live,
and my father...

635
00:54:03,157 --> 00:54:06,326
Such a good man
who tries to help Jews is killed.

636
00:54:06,660 --> 00:54:08,578
Don't you think that I am angry?

637
00:54:08,662 --> 00:54:11,623
But, you know, you don't understand Nathan.

638
00:54:13,292 --> 00:54:15,418
You don't know.

639
00:54:20,591 --> 00:54:24,093
Him, what he might do, you know.
I think...

640
00:54:24,178 --> 00:54:25,219
Sometimes I think...

641
00:54:25,304 --> 00:54:26,638
What do you think?

642
00:54:30,559 --> 00:54:32,352
What do you think, Polish baby?

643
00:54:32,436 --> 00:54:33,686
Oh, Nathan!

644
00:54:36,273 --> 00:54:37,941
You are all right?

645
00:54:38,025 --> 00:54:39,651
I'm all right.
What about the two of you?

646
00:54:41,320 --> 00:54:45,715
Yeah, well, I was so frightened, you know.
I was stupid.

647
00:54:46,992 --> 00:54:49,577
I got so scared, you know,
I thought something had happened to you.

648
00:54:49,662 --> 00:54:52,705
I would've called, but I didn't want
to take the chance of waking you up.

649
00:54:52,790 --> 00:54:54,707
We're on to something in our work.
Something big.

650
00:54:54,792 --> 00:54:56,084
- Yeah?
- Something very big.

651
00:54:56,168 --> 00:54:57,669
That's wonderful, Nathan.

652
00:55:01,382 --> 00:55:03,132
Yeah, wonderful.

653
00:55:14,186 --> 00:55:16,104
But you were here

654
00:55:18,607 --> 00:55:20,108
with Sophie.

655
00:55:21,235 --> 00:55:24,153
Yes, Stingo, you know, he...

656
00:55:24,238 --> 00:55:26,664
Stingo came home from his date.

657
00:55:28,033 --> 00:55:32,412
So I heard the door, I thought it was you.
So I run out, but...

658
00:55:33,080 --> 00:55:36,708
Anyway, I called him, I said,
"Why don't you come up for a drink?"

659
00:55:36,792 --> 00:55:42,171
Because I was worried
and he was a very good friend to me.

660
00:55:42,256 --> 00:55:44,924
He was keeping me company.

661
00:55:59,606 --> 00:56:04,068
So now you've seen my sanctum sanctorum.

662
00:56:05,571 --> 00:56:09,073
Now you know all of Nathan's
dark and dour secrets.

663
00:56:10,242 --> 00:56:11,701
Hardly.

664
00:56:18,625 --> 00:56:22,462
They wipe out six million Jews

665
00:56:24,423 --> 00:56:26,466
and the world lets them escape.

666
00:56:29,678 --> 00:56:33,431
Wanna join me in a little lynching party,
Southern boy?

667
00:56:33,557 --> 00:56:36,309
I expect you might have
a lot to teach me there.

668
00:56:37,770 --> 00:56:40,271
I'm going to call it a night here.

669
00:56:40,355 --> 00:56:42,065
Stingo, wait.

670
00:56:42,149 --> 00:56:45,151
Stingo is our best friend.
Why do you do that?

671
00:56:46,153 --> 00:56:48,863
He is our best friend.
He deserves only our thanks.

672
00:56:48,947 --> 00:56:51,616
Nathan, listen to me.

673
00:56:51,700 --> 00:56:56,287
I was frightened, I didn't know what I would do
if he had not been here.

674
00:57:02,878 --> 00:57:04,378
It's true.

675
00:57:14,181 --> 00:57:16,724
Forgive me, old buddy. I'm sorry.

676
00:57:17,434 --> 00:57:19,393
Of course my beloved Sophie is right.

677
00:57:19,478 --> 00:57:20,436
Yeah.

678
00:57:20,521 --> 00:57:22,146
I must've got crazy with the work, you know.

679
00:57:22,231 --> 00:57:23,231
I know you do.

680
00:57:23,315 --> 00:57:24,273
We're on to something big.

681
00:57:24,358 --> 00:57:25,358
I know, darling.

682
00:57:25,442 --> 00:57:28,277
I'm just another mad scientist,
we're all a bunch of nuts.

683
00:57:28,362 --> 00:57:30,321
Come on...

684
00:57:30,906 --> 00:57:32,323
I'm leaving.

685
00:57:33,951 --> 00:57:35,785
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

686
00:57:36,245 --> 00:57:37,411
Thank you for taking care of Sophie.

687
00:57:37,496 --> 00:57:39,372
Yeah, all right.

688
00:57:46,421 --> 00:57:48,881
Oh, Nathan!

689
00:57:50,134 --> 00:57:52,135
I'm sorry.

690
00:57:56,390 --> 00:57:58,307
Darling, I'm home.

691
00:58:03,105 --> 00:58:04,772
- Right!
- Are you all right?

692
00:58:04,857 --> 00:58:05,857
Yeah. Yeah.

693
00:58:05,941 --> 00:58:07,316
Are you sure?

694
00:58:07,401 --> 00:58:08,651
Yeah.

695
00:58:08,735 --> 00:58:11,487
Don't you catch things in the South?

696
00:58:13,866 --> 00:58:14,824
How's it going?

697
00:58:14,908 --> 00:58:16,450
Fine. It's going well.

698
00:58:16,535 --> 00:58:17,910
Think fast!

699
00:58:19,163 --> 00:58:20,204
Jesus!

700
00:58:22,708 --> 00:58:24,500
You came in and you wreck everything.

701
00:58:24,585 --> 00:58:27,795
Yetta, you know, always provides the best.

702
00:58:27,880 --> 00:58:29,672
The best you can find in Brooklyn!

703
00:58:30,799 --> 00:58:32,592
Oh, shit!

704
00:58:34,386 --> 00:58:37,388
Sophie should be taking a nap after work.

705
00:58:39,433 --> 00:58:41,684
She just doesn't sleep anymore.
Not since the war.

706
00:58:41,768 --> 00:58:42,768
How's it going?

707
00:58:42,853 --> 00:58:44,854
Yeah, fine. Thank you.

708
00:58:44,938 --> 00:58:46,439
Well, let me take a look at those.

709
00:58:46,523 --> 00:58:48,065
- No. No, no, no!
- Come on!

710
00:58:48,150 --> 00:58:51,861
I won't interfere, I won't make any comments.
I won't even...

711
00:58:51,945 --> 00:58:54,363
Look, I've shown this to no one.
No one's seen this.

712
00:58:54,448 --> 00:58:57,366
Yeah, but I'm not no one.
I'm a friend.

713
00:58:57,451 --> 00:58:58,743
Don't you have those down South?

714
00:58:58,827 --> 00:59:00,161
"Friend," a person attached to another

715
00:59:00,245 --> 00:59:02,163
by a feeling of personal regard or affection.

716
00:59:02,247 --> 00:59:03,873
- Look.
- One who offers assistance.

717
00:59:03,957 --> 00:59:04,916
A patron, a supporter.

718
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:07,084
Look, I vowed to myself
when I started this,

719
00:59:07,169 --> 00:59:08,252
I was not going to show it to anyone

720
00:59:08,337 --> 00:59:10,338
until I finish the very last sentence.

721
00:59:10,422 --> 00:59:12,465
Then only after that,
can I offer it to any person.

722
00:59:12,549 --> 00:59:13,691
Well...

723
00:59:15,219 --> 00:59:18,888
Okay. You mean, you're just terrified
that somebody won't like it.

724
00:59:18,972 --> 00:59:20,514
Terrified as in filled with terror.

725
00:59:20,599 --> 00:59:23,267
Terror, a sharp, overmastering, intense fear.

726
00:59:23,393 --> 00:59:25,561
- All right, all right!
- That which renders the victim chicken shit.

727
00:59:25,646 --> 00:59:27,688
Yeah, all right, all right.

728
00:59:29,650 --> 00:59:31,734
That will give you some idea.

729
00:59:31,818 --> 00:59:32,985
Oh, my God!

730
00:59:35,489 --> 00:59:37,531
What about the page in the typewriter?

731
00:59:37,616 --> 00:59:38,950
No, this is a...

732
00:59:39,993 --> 00:59:42,036
Nathan! Stop!

733
00:59:42,746 --> 00:59:44,247
All right.

734
00:59:45,582 --> 00:59:48,876
Stingo! What is the worst that can happen?

735
00:59:49,670 --> 00:59:51,837
I may discover you can't write! Bye!

736
00:59:51,922 --> 00:59:52,922
Shit! Fuck!

737
00:59:53,006 --> 00:59:54,715
Nathan, get back here!

738
00:59:54,800 --> 00:59:57,176
It's beyond your reach now, old buddy!

739
00:59:59,930 --> 01:00:01,430
Fine, right!

740
01:00:03,850 --> 01:00:05,351
Stingo, wait a minute!

741
01:00:06,311 --> 01:00:10,022
Wait! Nathan have ordered me
to take you to the movies.

742
01:00:10,107 --> 01:00:12,900
He made me your guardian
while he read that.

743
01:00:12,985 --> 01:00:16,612
Yes, so you don't do
no violence to yourself now.

744
01:00:21,994 --> 01:00:23,536
Nathan must have finished reading that.

745
01:00:23,620 --> 01:00:24,620
Yeah.

746
01:00:24,705 --> 01:00:25,913
Come on, let's go see.

747
01:00:25,998 --> 01:00:27,581
I think I'll wait in my room.

748
01:00:28,308 --> 01:00:29,500
No, come on!

749
01:00:29,584 --> 01:00:32,253
If he's got something to say to me,
let him come down and tell me.

750
01:00:32,337 --> 01:00:33,921
Yes, don't be silly.

751
01:01:19,426 --> 01:01:20,593
Bravo.

752
01:02:42,259 --> 01:02:43,759
On this bridge,

753
01:02:45,720 --> 01:02:49,098
on which so many great American writers
have stood and reached out for words

754
01:02:49,182 --> 01:02:51,183
to give America its voice,

755
01:02:54,312 --> 01:02:57,231
looking toward the land
that gave us Whitman,

756
01:02:57,524 --> 01:03:02,194
from its Eastern edge dreamt his country's future
and gave it words,

757
01:03:05,073 --> 01:03:06,532
on this span

758
01:03:07,951 --> 01:03:10,786
of which Thomas Wolfe and Hart Crane wrote,

759
01:03:13,874 --> 01:03:18,461
we welcome Stingo
into that pantheon of the gods,

760
01:03:19,963 --> 01:03:23,340
whose words are all we know of immortality.

761
01:03:29,764 --> 01:03:31,974
To Stingo!

762
01:03:43,904 --> 01:03:46,989
<i>How could I have failed
to have the most helpless crush</i>

763
01:03:47,073 --> 01:03:51,494
<i>on such a generous mind
and life-enlarging mentor?</i>

764
01:03:52,537 --> 01:03:57,124
<i>Nathan was utterly, fatally glamorous.</i>

765
01:03:58,251 --> 01:03:59,460
Sophie!

766
01:04:01,087 --> 01:04:02,630
We did it!

767
01:04:03,590 --> 01:04:05,549
- Stingo!
- Nathan!

768
01:04:10,972 --> 01:04:12,014
We did it!

